\section{Intruductiom}

Before the 1990s, image denoising primarily relied on linear smoothing methods such as \textbf{Gaussian Filtering}. However, these methods inevitably blurred the edges and details of the image while filtering out noise. To overcome this limitation, Rudin, Osher, and Fatemi proposed the famous ROF model (i.e., Total Variation TV regularization) in 1992. By introducing the $L_1$ norm as a prior constraint, this model successfully achieved the goal of effectively preserving image edge features while removing noise. Its mathematical model is as follows:
\begin{equation}
\min_{u} \left\{ \frac{1}{2} \| u - f \|_2^2 + \lambda \| \nabla u \|_1 \right\}
\end{equation}
Despite the excellent mathematical properties of the ROF model, early solvers based on \textbf{Partial Differential Equations (PDE)} faced bottlenecks of low computational efficiency and poor numerical stability. This situation was significantly improved in the 21st century:

\textbf{Algorithmic Breakthrough:} Around 2004, Daubechies et al. proposed ISTA (Iterative Soft-Thresholding Algorithm). This algorithm cleverly solved the optimization problem of the $L_1$ norm term being non-differentiable at the origin through the \textbf{Proximal Operator}, providing an efficient computational framework for sparse representation and image reconstruction.

\textbf{Theoretical Renaissance:} At the same time, the \textbf{ADMM (Alternating Direction Method of Multipliers)} theory, which originated in the 1970s, gained new vitality in the field of image processing. In 2011, re-popularized by Boyd et al., ADMM quickly became the mainstream algorithm for solving total variation regularization problems due to its excellent variable splitting strategy, high potential for parallelization, and robustness in handling complex constrained problems.

\section*{Research Objective}
This paper aims to compare the denoising effects of traditional denoising algorithms such as BM3D with TV-transform-based ISTA, its upgraded version FISTA, and the ADMM algorithm. Specifically, since the optimization objectives of the latter three are the same, the denoising solution is unique; therefore, we compare the computational speeds of these three. Preliminary experimental results show that BM3D has a significantly better effect on removing Gaussian noise than several algorithms based on TV transform, but its performance is worse than TV transform after adding a portion of salt-and-pepper noise.

